-- Classical Collapse Example
--
-- Demonstrates the {0,1} collapse theorem:
-- When credences are restricted to Bool, CredTT becomes MLTT.
--
-- Key properties:
-- 1. Neighbourhoods are singletons (no interior points)
-- 2. Stable1(true) and Unstable0(false) are trivially true
-- 3. No c satisfies c = neg c (unlike [0,1] where c = 1/2)

-- In {0,1} mode, credences can only be 0 or 1

-- Postulate: a term at credence 1 (the only "true" credence)
postulate a : A [ 1 ]

-- In classical mode:
-- - 1 * 1 = 1 (applying definite functions to definite values gives definite results)
-- - 1 * 0 = 0 (any undefined step makes the whole derivation undefined)
-- - neg 0 = 1 (negation of false is true)
-- - neg 1 = 0 (negation of true is false)

-- Stability is trivial in Bool:
-- - true is always Stable1 (neighbourhood = {true})
-- - false is always Unstable0 (neighbourhood = {false})
-- - No interior points exist (no c strictly between 0 and 1)

-- The Godel fixed point c = neg c has NO solution in Bool:
-- - If c = true, then neg c = false != true
-- - If c = false, then neg c = true != false
-- This is why classical incompleteness manifests as undecidability.

-- In [0,1], the fixed point exists: c = 1/2
-- CredTT can express this, classical logic cannot.

derive result : A [ 1 ] from a by trivial
